<HEAD>Saddam's Babylonian Dream Dashed by Invasion of Kuwait</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BABYLON, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief archaeologist was picking dates
from a tree to kill time and ease her boredom in the legendary
gardens of Babylon, where Saddam Hussein wants to rebuild one of
the wonders of the ancient world.
   Shafeka Mohammed Jaafar has no work because Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait stalled efforts to restore the glory of Babylon, whose kings
ruled an empire that stretched over most of the Middle East.
   Saddam, the self-styled ``Knight of the Arab nation,'' fancies
himself a modern-day Nebuchadnezzar, Babylon's most famous king.
   Iraqi laborers, many of them military reservists, have been
called up to bolster Saddam's army facing more than 330,000
multinational troops massed in the deserts of Saudi Arabia.
   Also, thousands of Sudanese and Egyptian laborers fled Babylon
after the Aug. 2 invasion.
   An estimated $100 million was spent on the project over the last
decade. But funds have became scarce as Saddam juggles a cash
squeeze brought on by the U.N.-supported embargo on Iraqi trade and
oil exports.
   A lone soldier with an AK-47 rifle now stands guard at the
entrance to Nebuchadnezzar's partially rebuilt Babylon.
   ``Before, our president used to visit us regularly, but after he
liberated Kuwait, he has not come even once,'' said Mrs. Jaafar,
47.
   ``He's very busy now fighting Zionist and imperialist forces,''
she added, nibbling at her freshly collected dates.
   More than 2,500 years ago, Babylon rose in the land of
Mesopotamia on the Euphrates River.
   Under Nebuchadnezzar, Babylon entered its golden age. Its
Hanging Gardens, one of the so-called ``seven wonders of the
world,'' long ago crumbled to dust. An artificial lake has been dug
to irrigate the future gardens.
   For 1,200 years, the Babylonians ruled an empire that flourished
as a cultural, religious and commercial center. According to some
traditions, the Garden of Eden in the Bible was in this land
between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers.
   Under Saddam, a new Babylon has begun to rise again.
   An estimated 15 million bricks, baked as they were centuries
ago, have been used to rebuild the city's monuments. The plans are
based on archaeological evidence, cuneiform texts of Babylonian
characters and descriptions from ancient historians.
   Every 100th brick bears the name of Saddam in Arabic proclaiming
the Iraqi leader's efforts to reconstruct Babylon.
   To Saddam and many Iraqi officials, restoring Babylon is more
than an archaeological venture.
   ``After centuries we've got Saddam, a great leader who's going
to restore the past glory of our land. It's only Saddam who can do
that,'' Mrs. Jaafar said as she guided reporters through the ruins
of the 8-square-mile city.
   Iraqis are constantly told that Saddam can restore the lost
glory of Babylon. The state-owned news media and dozens of books
stress that Babylon once controlled the land that is now Iraq,
Syria, Jordan, Lebanon, Kuwait and Israel.
   Reminders of Saddam are everywhere in Babylon, as they are in
the rest of Iraq.
   On the 55-mile journey from Baghdad south to Babylon, past oil
refineries and anti-aircraft batteries, Saddam's portraits appear
on almost every building, at gasoline stations and fruit stands.
   The road to Babylon branches off the highway before the town of
Hilla. At the entrance to modern Babylon, a small town of one-story
houses, stands a huge portrait of Saddam wearing an Arab keffiyeh
headdress with a white dove of peace fluttering over his head.
   ``Saddam is no ordinary leader and no ordinary president,'' said
Mrs. Jaafar. ``He is the new Nebuchadnezzar.''
   Portraits of Saddam and Nebuchadnezzar are displayed
side-by-side in Babylon and Baghdad.
   In the souvenir shop at Babylon, pamphlets and books carry
portraits of Saddam after the title page. Nebuchadnezzar is hailed
for his dual role as a civilian and military leader.
   The same image is projected in Baghdad in portraits showing
Saddam in fatigues or in Western suits.
   The Iraqi media refers to Saddam as ``father-leader,'' ``hero of
national liberation'' and ``standard-bearer of Islam.''
   Nebuchadnezzar is projected to Iraqis as the defender of the
``Arab nation,'' even though he lived 1,000 years before there was
such a concept.
   Nebuchadnezzar conquered Jerusalem, took the people of Israel
into captivity for 50 years and fought for years against the
Persians - not unlike Saddam's 1980-88 war with Iran, the
modern-day Persia.
   Nebuchadnezzar died in 562 B.C., 24 years before the city was
captured by the Persians.
</TEXT>
