<CAPTION>  Photos (2), map; PHOTO: An Assyrian plaque, above, in the Baghdad museum dates
from the 8th century B.C.; PHOTO: the image below shows a classic mythological
monster: a winged bull with the head of a man and body of a lion.; MAP: Ron
Coddington -- Mercury News; Iraq's ancient landmarks  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  HUMAN; RELIGION; HISTORY; IRAQ; KUWAIT; MIDEAST; WAR; RESULT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  AS THE cost of the Persian Gulf war slowly sinks into the collective psyche,
it is becoming evident that the toll of war will be measured in more than
human life.;    There is another, more intangible treasure at risk, buried
deep beneath the embattled Iraqi landscape. And scholars are pondering the
irony that the full technological force of Western civilization is now focused
on bombing its cradle.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Religion &amp; Ethics  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BOMBING THE CRADLE
WILL THE RAVAGES OF MODERN WARFARE FOREVER
WIPE AWAY THE WONDERS OF ANCIENT CIVILIZATION?  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
War in the Gulf
See related stories page 1C of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In time and tradition, the roots of modern Iraq run deep -- all the way
back to the Garden of Eden, which some biblical scholars believe was located
on the swampy plain between the Tigris and Euphrates, near the present-day
city of Basra.;    Here, more than 6,000 years ago in the Fertile Crescent of
Mesopotamia, Western civilization began to unfold. Here, archaeologists have
found the earliest evidence of organized human society.;    Despite assurances
by President Bush and Pentagon officials that shrines and places of
archaeological significance would be avoided in the air war over Iraq, a grim
reality of the current war is that civilization's ancient treasures occupy
sites of strategic military importance.;    "I don't want it to seem as if I
care more about ancient pottery than I do about people. The human cost of this
war is my greatest concern," says David Stronach, professor of Near East
archaeology at the University of California, Berkeley.;    "But I'm worried
about the ruins of the ancient cities," he says. "The power of the weapons
that are being used is very alarming. Certain mistakes are bound to be made.
There will be losses that we will all regret.";    Over succeeding centuries
in the ancient empires of Sumer, Assyria and Babylonia, great cities were
built and fine art was crafted. The first words were inscribed on soft clay
tablets, the first laws formulated and the first epic poem composed. The
ancient city of Babylon, whose Hanging Gardens were among the wonders of the
world, was also the place centuries later that the Talmud, the great source of
Jewish law, was written. With the rise of Islam also rose Baghdad, a center of
learning and literature.;    Until the invasion of Kuwait ground all
archaeological projects to a halt, Stronach had directed a UC team that was
unearthing the ruins of Nineveh, where the biblical prophet Jonah is believed
to be buried. Nineveh is within the boundaries of the modern-day city of Mosul
in northern Iraq.;    Mosul is also considered to be a prime military target,
home to three air-bases and two weapons manufacturing plants. But it is not
the only military installation that has been built near sacred or historic
sites: A concentration of Saddam Hussein's elite Republican Guards is reported
to be south of Ur, legendary birthplace of Abraham. Rocket and ballistic
missile plants are believed to be located at Kerbala, the city sacred to
Shi'ite Muslims as the place where Husayn, grandson of Mohammed, was slain.;  
 Burying treasures;  The city of Samarra, north of Baghdad, where some of the
finest examples of Islamic architecture are preserved, is also the location of
one of Saddam's main weapons plants. And Basra, the legendary site of the
Garden of Eden, is also the location of a major oil refinery.;    One monument
Stronach considers particularly vulnerable is the Arch of Ctesiphon, just
south of Baghdad. Built in 550 A.D. as the main hall of a palace, this soaring
arch is a rare surviving example of the abilities of ancient architects to use
brick as if it were light as air.;    "This is the longest span of any
unsupported baked-brick arch in the world," Stronach says. "One shudders at
the possibility of it being blown to bits.";    Stronach also is concerned
about the fate of the Iraq Museum in Baghdad, repository of priceless
treasures, including the cuneiform tablets on which are inscribed the Epic of
Gilgamesh, a poem that is the first written literature in history. Though many
of the holdings of the museum were housed underground during the eight-year
Iran-Iraq war, Stronach and other scholars wonder how the artifacts will fare
under the intense firepower of the technologically superior allied forces.;   
"There are reliefs from the ancient Assyrian civilization, royal tomb
offerings and cuneiform writings that have yet to be deciphered," Stronach
says. "These are the treasures of a priceless civilization that are in a very
real sense the property of all the peoples of the world.";    To Ali Muzafar
Khan, a Shi'ite Muslim from San Jose, the bombing raids threaten not only
precious architecture but the religious leader of many Shi'ites worldwide.;   
The Grand Ayatollah Abolghassen Khoi, the highest ranking Shi'ite Muslim
authority in Iraq, lives in the sacred city of Najaf.;    "We are really,
really scared about his safety and the safety of thousands of Shi'ites who
have gone there to seek refuge," says Khan, who adds that many Muslims have no
illusions about what it will take to oust Saddam Hussein from power.;    "He
is a stubborn man and to win this war will mean the destruction of Iraq. We
are praying for the safety of the people.";    Cultural blackout;  David
Pleins, an archaeologist and professor of religious studies at Santa Clara
University, equates the current blackout of news about civilian casualties in
Iraq with the "cultural blackout" of awareness in many people's minds about
the value of ancient civilizations.;    Such lack of awareness, he says,
allows people to harden themselves to the loss of blood and cultural treasure
that are the consequences of war.;    "We don't understand," Pleins says. "We
don't really know how devastating this is in terms of human life, cultural
life or historical life. There is a complete blackout of understanding.";   
Pleins, who has done most of his research in neighboring Jordan, says that in
the end, archaeology leaves him with an overriding sense of irony.;    "It
seems that we're always studying the engines of war: civilizations that are
built up and brought down with military conflicts," he says. "In the end,
we're left with the enduring legacy of the power of the war machine.";   
Stronach agrees. Before events forced him to leave Iraq, the UC archaeologist
directed a team that unearthed the remnants of an ancient war: skeletons of
soldiers, lances, arrowheads and other weapons. The remains led Stronach to
piece together a theory about how Nineveh, which was ruled by a brutal tyrant,
was defeated in the 6th century B.C. in a relatively brief conflict with the
technologically superior allied armies of Babylonia and Media.;    Stronach,
who expects to return to Iraq and finish his work some day, refrains from
drawing any parallels between the battle of Nineveh and the Persian Gulf war.;
   "But at the very least," he says. "I can appreciate the ironies."  </TEXT>
