<LEADPARA>  The Bush administration accused Iraqi President Saddam Hussein Wednesday of
endangering one of the world's most precious archaeological treasures by
parking two warplanes near the ruins of a temple in the ancient city of Ur.;  
 Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney said the Iraqi military command has placed
the two Soviet-made MiG-21 fighter-bombers "right next to the pyramid" at Ur,
a reference to the famous ziggurat of Ur-Nammu, the king who reigned over the
city-state about 2100 B.C.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  IRAQ PARKING JETS NEAR RUINS OF ANCIENT TEMPLE,
U.S. SAYS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  WAR IN THE GULF
See also related stories on pages 1A and 16-18A of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Ur was the capital of Sumer and the birthplace of the Biblical patriarch
Abraham. Its ziggurat, or temple, is perhaps the most spectacular
archaeological remain in Mesopotamia, the area between the Tigris and
Euphrates rivers known as the cradle of civilization.;    Cheney said the
decision to park the planes by the temple shows that Saddam should bear the
blame for unintended destruction of civilian neighborhoods, cultural sites and
other non-military facilities by allied bombers.;    Cheney, speaking to the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce, said the two MiGs were spotted by "satellite imagery
obtained just this morning." Saddam's regime placed the planes at the site
"obviously (in) an effort to use the archaeologically significant facility to
protect his military capabilities," he said.;    Contacted independently, two
specialists in Near Eastern archaeology confirmed that for several years
Saddam has placed military installations and equipment near ancient cultural
sites.;    Augusta McMahon, an archaeological researcher at the University of
Chicago, said Ur is bordered by and partly covered by Tellil, a military
airfield west of Nasiriyah, Iraq, a modern riverfront city. Both the modern
city and the airfield have been targets of allied bombing.;    McGuire Gibson,
professor of Mesopotamian archaeology at the University of Chicago, said he
last visited the Ur site a decade ago and noted that the airfield was about a
mile from the remains of the ziggurat.;    Gibson and McMahon expressed
concern that most of the archaeological sites left by successive ancient
civilizations that flourished in the area are now at risk, partly because many
are surrounded by cities, factories and other possible targets.;    For
example, in an area of northern Iraq once known as Assyria, the site of the
ancient city of Nineveh is surrounded by the modern industrial suburbs of
Mosul. McMahon, who has been to digs at Nineveh in recent years, said Mosul's
main oil storage tank is "right on a partially excavated tell (mound) next to
the palace of the Assyrian kings.";    Located nearby, said Gibson, is the
partly excavated throne room of Sennacherib, an Assyrian king. Covered by a
corrugated metal roof, the large oblong structure contains a number of
priceless relief carvings still affixed to the original walls.;    "That could
have been targeted as a storage shed," Gibson said. "I'm sure the oil tank has
been hit.";    McMahon said a rumor swept through the large Iraqi-American
population in Detroit in recent days that a massive brick arch in a
third-century palace in Ctesiphon, some 20 miles south of Baghdad, had fallen
in the bombing. But there has been no corroboration so far, she said.;   
Gibson said he was apprehensive about what he assumed was a lack of knowledge
on the part of U.S. military planners about Iraq's rich archaeological legacy.  </TEXT>
