<HEAD>Iraqi Jews, Haunted by Babylon, Fear War</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tawfic Sofer, a retired cloth merchant and
caretaker of Baghdad's main synagogue, peered through the makeshift
peephole of an iron gate 10 feet high.
   When ordered by two government officials, from State Security
and the Information Ministry, the 65-year-old Iraqi Jew unlocked
the gate and swung it open.
   ``Welcome, welcome,'' he said several times in Arabic, his eyes
on the cars parked outside.
   Satisfied that the officials were alone, except for a foreign
reporter, he guided the group to the synagogue.
   President Saddam Hussein's government sometimes allows visits by
Western news media to the synagogue in downtown Baghdad, but
requires Iraqi officials to accompany them for ``security reasons''
that are not explained.
   Reporters are discouraged from visiting the synagogue on the
Jewish Sabbath, which runs from sundown Friday to sundown Saturday.
   Reminders of Saddam are omnipresent in Iraq, and the synagogue
is no exception. His portrait is on two calendars that hang on the
wall at the entrance.
   The square, white two-story synagogue was built in 1942 in the
middle of a bazaar.
   Its walls are covered with Scriptures written in Hebrew and
there are many shelves of old books. The synagogue's Torah scrolls,
the handwritten five books of Moses that form the foundation of the
Jewish faith, are on a raised platform, concealed by a black and
gold curtain.
   ``It is a very rich collection,'' said Sofer, a bachelor who
gave up his business to tend the synagogue after the last caretaker
died two years ago. ``We are fine and we do not want war. We are a
very small community, but we are surviving.''
   About 600 Jews live in Baghdad, 200 more in the port city of
Basra, 100 in the northern city of Mosul and 100 or so in other
areas of Iraq, he said.
   Iraq had a flourishing Jewish community of doctors, lawyers,
professors and businessmen with 65 synagogues when Iraq gained
political independence from Britain in 1932.
   Only two synagogues still function. More than 120,000 Iraqi Jews
moved to Israel soon after the Jewish state was born in 1948.
   Sofer said his ancestors and those of most Iraqi Jews came to
Baghdad from Babylon centuries ago. More than 2,500 years ago, King
Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon conquered Jerusalem and carried the
captive Children of Israel back to the land between the Tigris and
the Euphrates rivers.
   Saddam often is compared with Nebuchadnezzar in the Baghdad of
today. Iraqi officials describe the Jews of Babylon as an ancient
Fifth Column who helped Persian invaders take the city.
   According to the oft-told story, which does not appear in the
Bible, the Babylonian Jews advised King Cyrus to destroy dams on
the Euphrates, thus lowering water levels in moats around the city
so his troops could enter.
   ``We do have problems,'' Sofer said of Baghdad's remaining Jews.
He paused, looked at the Iraqi officials and continued:
   ``Our problems are marriages. We don't have enough young men to
marry. We have at least 25 girls ready to marry, but there are not
enough eligible men.''
   Sofer said Iraqi Jews hav  only one shohet, the butcher who
slaughters animals and prepares the meat according to ancient
Jewish law.
   ``It is a big problem, but we are trying to solve it,'' Sofer
said. ``He has to work overtime. There is no other way. When he is
sick, we have a major problem.''
   ``We are very lucky'' that two rabbis serve Baghdad, he said.
   Like all Iraqis interviewed, of whatever faith, Sofer would not
say if people live in fear of Saddam.
   When asked whether he feared persecution if the U.S.-led
multinational force in Saudi Arabia attacked in an effort to force
Iraq out of Kuwait, he said: ``We pray there is no war.''
   ``The people here do not trust us, but we are not bothered. But
if there is war, we may face problems.'' Sofer refused to
elaborate.
   Iraq, a predominantly Moslem country, denies any persecution of
Jews.
   ``We have Jewish people studying in university,'' said an
Information Ministry official, who cannot be named under government
regulations. ``They are also in business.''
   He said Jewish businessmen, like their Moslem counterparts, were
free to travel outside Iraq.
   Saddam's government, however, carries on a regular propaganda
program to ``expose the Zionist movement's imperialist goals.''
</TEXT>
