<LEADPARA>  Is the Persian Gulf war the ultimate voyage toward a fiery end before a
blissful beginning? Will there be, as the Bible says, a battle of Armageddon,
followed by the second coming of Christ?;    Since Iraq overran Kuwait last
summer, a fervor has been building among millions of evangelical Christians
nationwide.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ARMAGEDDON? OR JUST ANOTHER WAR?  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  War in the Gulf.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Many pastors are trying to address it directly, and mostly calmly, with
answers straight out of the Bible.;    Some evangelicals, such as author and
scholar the Rev. Charles Dyer, see evidence of "the three signposts" found in
the Bible that Armageddon is near.;    "First, Israel must be in existence,
which was put in place in 1948. Second, world power must be revived in the
boundaries of the ancient Roman Empire, which we see beginning in the
realignment of European nations," Dyer said. "And third, Babylon must be
rebuilt.";    But instead of declaring, as does Revelation 16:17, "It is
over," many televangelists, "end-time" scholars and pastors are qualifying
their sermons, saying the current conflict might be a "foreshadowing,"
"prelude" or "preview" to the final conflagration -- but not the main event.; 
  "A lot of us are aware, watching and alerted to what's happening," said Greg
Laurie, a radio evangelist in Southern California.;    "After all, any time
something happens in the Middle East where the security of Israel is
threatened, it could tip the first domino of the prophetic calendar.";   
Shortly after the war erupted last month, Laurie began reviewing the Book of
Revelation, the prophetic story that details the world's last days, with his
Monday night Bible study class at the Calvary Chapel in Santa Ana.;    Laurie,
like many others, does not go too far out on a limb.;    "I'm not the kind of
person that makes statements that put me out there," he said. "I'm not a
prophet, and we have to be careful that we don't eat our words in two
months.";    America's 50 million evangelical Christians interpret Bible
stories as containing varying degrees of prophecy. Some see these rich and
vivid stories as highly metaphorical, to be read for their moral value and
sagacity.;    Yet there always have been those who combed the Bible,
particularly in the books of Daniel, Revelation and Ezekiel, for detailed
scenarios of the prophetic panorama, scrutinizing them not only for their
lessons about good and evil but also for times, dates and locations of
upcoming events.;    Over time, some have even pinpointed the "end time,"
naming Hitler, Mussolini and even former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger as
the Antichrist who would drive civilization over the brink. These days,
however, only a few venture to be that specific.;    Among those who interpret
the Bible literally, speculation has been focused on the words of the enemy
himself.;    Although Iraqi President Saddam Hussein takes his cues from
Islam, he has startled many Christians with his religious imagery -- such as
when he said after the first allied air strike on Baghdad that it would lead
to "the mother of all battles" or when he said he had rebuilt Iraq to the
glory of ancient Babylon and likened himself to Nebuchadnezzar, the Babylonian
king who destroyed Jerusalem in the sixth century B.C.;    "The Bible does say
that Babylon will be revealed in last days," Laurie said. "Could this be
Babylon actually being rebuilt?";    The Rev. Ezra Williams, senior pastor of
the Bethel Assembly Gospel Church in Harlem, said his Sunday services have
been flooded not only with people who are questioning "the Bible relevancy" of
Operation Desert Storm but also by those who feel unable to cope with the
increasing economic turmoil.;    "I tell my people that we are living in a
crucial time in history when nations are positioning for the final battle of
Armageddon and they must do what they can for their brothers and sisters,"
Williams said. "But I don't say when it will happen. I just feel we must be
ready.";    In a poll taken a week after the war started, the Gallup
organization asked 1,011 people in telephone interviews whether they thought
this battle would be Armageddon: 15 percent said yes; 74 percent answered no;
11 percent were unsure.;    Yet so many people are wondering that popular
books about biblical prophecy are outselling more secular treatises about the
troubled region. In the last 10 weeks, 600,000 copies of John F. Walvoord's
recently updated "Armageddon, Oil and the Middle East Crisis" have been sold;
300,000 more copies are being distributed by evangelist Billy Graham.;   
Walvoord, 80, is considered the leading scholar of this very dramatic school
of biblical prophecy and was for many years the head of the Dallas Theological
Seminary, long an academic center of literalist study.;    Besides Walvoord,
Dyer, professor and dean of enrollment at Dallas Theological Seminary, has
seen this attention translate into "best-selling author" status.;    Dyer's
"The Rise of Babylon: Sign of the End Times," focuses on Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein's efforts to rebuild the city of Babylon. Tyndale House
Publishers reports 129,000 copies of the book were distributed since its
release on Jan. 15, the deadline by which Hussein was to withdraw from Kuwait
or face U.S. military force.  </TEXT>
