<HEAD>Agatha Christie Remembered _ in Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a little mud-brick room on the ruins of
old Nimrud, north of Baghdad, an ordinary-looking Engishwoman
retired each day from the fierce Assyrian sun to plot murder.
   Locals on the archaeological dig knew the woman as Mrs.
Mallowan, a photographer. But the books she wrote in the crude
little room bore another name.
   Agatha Christie.
   As her archaelogist husband, Sir Max Mallowan, helped chart the
dawn of history in the desert hills, Miss Christie sat among
Mesopotamian relics and conjured cases for the fictional detectives
of her mystery novels.
   Her years after World War II at Nimrud, one of the great cities
of the Assyrian empire in 1400-600 B.C., capped decades of Middle
Eastern travel and archaeological work that left traces scattered
throughout her 77 books.
   Miss Christie first arrived in the Middle East in 1907, aged 17,
for her debutante season in Cairo, Egypt.
   ``We spent three months there and I went to five dances every
week,'' she recalled in an autobiography in 1965.
   She later set at least two novels in Egypt: ``Death on The
Nile'' and ``Death Comes As the End,'' a tale of love and murder in
the Thebes of 2000 B.C.
   A deeper relationship with the area began in the 1930s when she
took the Orient Express across Europe to Turkey and continued on by
train and car across the wild Syrian desert to Baghdad.
   There she met Mallowan. They spent most of the next 20 years
bouncing between Britain and archaeological digs in Iraq and Syria.
   ``She was very unprepossessing to look at,'' said the Iraqi
writer and critic Jabra Ibrahim Jabra, who first met her in 1949.
   ``She was a very charming woman to talk to, very attentive ...
with a dry sense of humor. You wouldn't know she was the great
Agatha Christie.''
   Jabra said she lived with Mallowan in the former home of King
Ali on the bank of the Tigris River. The house and its surroundings
made a cameo appearance in her 1951 spy novel, ``They Came to
Baghdad'':
   ``There was the persistent honking of motor horns, the cries of
vendors of various wares. There were hot disputes between small
groups of people who seemed ready to murder each other but were
really fast friends.''
   All of that seems true today, although the donkeys, horses and
mud-brick homes she described in the book are rapidly giving way to
Brazilian-made Volkswagens and concrete high-rises.
   The dusty, bouncing road to Babylon she recounts in that novel
is now a smooth highway.
   And the ``meaningless pile of ruined mud and burnt brick'' she
found there has been resurrected into a freshly whitewashed
reconstruction of King Nebuchadnezzar's 6th century B.C. capital.
   Baghdad's Rashid Street is still a major downtown thoroughfare,
as it was when Miss Christie first visited, although some of its
fancier buildings have decayed.
   The Tigris Palace Hotel where Miss Christie stayed still stands,
although she would never recognize the remodeled and cut-rate Ibn
Haitham as the graceful hotel that figured in her 1935 book,
``Murder in Mesopotamia.''
   British and American expatriates in Baghdad still gather weekly
in a play-reading circle that claims Miss Christie as an early
member.
   Archaeologists at the British Expedition office in Baghdad say
some of their furnishings are rumored to have once graced her
living room.
   Her mud-brick workroom still stands at Nimrud, although it's now
used as a storage room.
   The creator of the prim and proper Miss Marple has even had the
honor of a banned book. Her remembrances of life on the digs,
``Come, Tell Me How You Live,'' was blocked by Iraqi censors
because it was considered to be ``derogatory.''
   Miss Christie is still remembered at the charming but decrepit
Baron's Hotel in Aleppo, Syria, where she reportedly worked on
several books.
   But the owners of the Orient Palace Hotel in Damascus, the
Syrian capital, where she stayed on her first visit to the region,
did not recall her.
   The once-elegant hotel still has the marble floors and dim
lights she described. But paint peels from the hallway walls and
portraits of Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini peer sternly out
from the front windows.
   The Orient Palace now accommodates the families of Iranians
killed in the war with Iraq who are flown to Damascus on state-paid
vacations.
   The Nabatean ruins at Petra in Jordan, backdrop for
``Appointment With Death,'' are no longer, as Miss Christie wrote,
``a full day's motor run across the desert'' from Amman, the
kingdom's capital.
   But Petra itself _ ``as real as _ as raw beef,'' she described
it _ remains the same.
   Writer-critic Jabra said most of Miss Christie's books are about
``the English in a foreign country'' and had little to do with the
locals.
   ``Her geographical descriptions are quite good, but her contact
with Iraqis was limited,'' he said.
   But he added she was ``very well-liked by Iraqis who knew her.''
She returned that affection in her autobiography.
   ``How much I have loved that part of the world,'' she wrote. ``I
love it still and I always shall.''
</TEXT>
