with cuneiform writing is displayed in Tel Hazor, Israel, on Tuesday.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  PAST; HISTORY; WRITING; BOOK; RECORD; FOUND; ISRAEL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  An archaeologist Tuesday displayed an ancient tablet found last week that he
believes is part of the lost royal archive of Hazor, once the largest city in
biblical Israel.;    If found in its entirety, the archive could yield
priceless knowledge of civilization more than 3,500 years ago, said
archaeologist Amnon Ben-Tor of Jerusalem's Hebrew University.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ANCIENT TABLET MAY BELONG TO LOST ARCHIVE
ARTIFACT COULD LEAD TO CITY'S ROYAL RECORDS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     A major Canaanite commercial center in the second millennium B.C.,
mentioned in the Bible as "the head of all those (Canaanite) kingdoms," Hazor
was burned down by the warrior Joshua, according to the book of Joshua.;   
About nine miles north of the Sea of Galilee, Hazor once covered 200 acres and
was eight times bigger than Jerusalem at the time, said Ben-Tor, who heads an
Israeli-Spanish-American excavation.;    Iron Age find;  He said the
matchbox-sized clay tablet dates to the 18th or 17th century B.C. It was found
last week in a section belonging to a period centuries later, the Iron Age, he
said.;    Ben-Tor said he assumes that Iron Age people removed the tablet from
its original site while digging around to make bricks.;    The tablet contains
19 names in cuneiform script and is written in Akkadian, a language of
commerce and politics of the time. Each name is preceded by an amount of
weight in silver supposedly received from the king of Hazor.;    "I am certain
that this tablet is part of the royal archive," said Ben-Tor, adding that the
collection might still be under ruins now being excavated that are thought to
be the palace of Hazor.;    Some of the names on the tablet are of Emorites, a
western Semitic tribe.;    There is also a fragment of a name believed to be
of a weather god worshiped by western Semitic people, said Ben-Tor.;    He
said only five examples of writing from this period had been found.;   
Thousands of tablets in Syria; However, tens of thousands of tablets dating
back to the 18th century B.C. have been found in the ancient Syrian city of
Mari on the Euphrates River.;    Among the Syrian documents are 14 letters
written by the king of Hazor to Mari, Ben-Tor said.;    "Where is the return
mail? It must be here," he said.;    Hazor was the first major dig by Israeli
archaeologist Yigael Yadin, in 1955-'58. According to the daily Jerusalem
Post, shortly before his death in 1984 Yadin said he believed he knew where
the archives were and was planning to look for them.;    According to the
dramatic account in the book of Joshua, the leader first defeated a coalition
of city-states led by Jabin, King of Hazor.;    Then, according to Joshua
11:10-11, Joshua "turned back at that time, and took Hazor, and smote the king
thereof with the sword . . . and he burnt Hazor with fire. . . . But for the
cities that stood on their mounds, Israel burned none of them, save Hazor only
-- that did Joshua burn."  </TEXT>
