<HEAD>Iraqis View War With Bravado, Fatalism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqis hardened by eight years of war with
Iran seem almost casual about the formidable buildup of U.S.
firepower across the border in Saudi Arabia.
   There is some concern about the embargo on trade with Iraq
ordered by the United Nations after Baghdad seized Kuwait, and some
suspicions about the causes of the crisis.
   But there is no smell of war along the noisy, bustling avenues
of this ancient capital.
   Instead, Iraqis willing to talk with Western reporters view the
threat of war with a mixture of bravado and Arab fatalism.
   ``What can I do about it?'' shrugged Mahdi Kathom, a 30-year-old
vegetable vendor in central Baghdad. ``If it happens, it is because
God lets it happen. There is nothing to do about it.''
   ``God willing, our president will solve this,'' said one
middle-aged woman who declined to give her name. ``Saddam Hussein
is a strong and wise man.''
   Many Iraqis question the motives of President Bush in sending
troops and warplanes to Saudi Arabia. But a few, speaking privately
in this rigidly controlled society, say they are suspicious about
their own leader and his reasons for provoking the crisis.
   Some say Saddam underestimated the U.S. reaction and a few
others voice suspicions that he triggered the crisis partly to
challenge the Americans and raise his standing in the Arab world.
   For eight years, Saddam told his people they were fighting Iran
for control over the Shatt al-Arab waterway that spills into the
northern Persian Gulf.
   Then, on Aug. 12, just 10 days after the invasion of Kuwait,
Saddam acknowledged Iran's claim to shared sovereignty over the
waterway that some Iraqis believe they bought with the blood of
their loved ones.
   Saddam's peace overture secured his vulnerable eastern border,
freeing troops to confront the U.S. buildup.
   Some Iraqis say they now wonder why Saddam gave in on the
waterway and why he chose to invade Kuwait.
   But while a few quietly mumble their suspicions, Iraqis who
spoke openly defended the invasion and occupation of the country
they have long considered a part of Iraq, wrongfully separated from
the motherland by British colonial rulers.
   ``Forget Kuwait, it is a dream. There is no Kuwait,'' said one
Baghdad taxi driver.
   A few Iraqis said they have heard frightening assessments of
American military might on foreign radio broadcasts by the British
Broadcasting Corp. and Voice of America.
   But the state-controlled press has focused on dissent in the
West against the sanctions and the troop buildup. The Iraqi press
also has disparaged the ability of U.S. troops to fight against
battle-hardened Iraqis in the desert.
   Near the center of Baghdad stands the Monument of Saddam's
Qaddissiya Martyrs, a tribute to the dead of the Iran-Iraq war,
named after Babylon's victory over the Persians in 600 B.C.
   The marble monument covered with aqua tiles is in the form of
two halves of an Islamic dome. It is split to symbolize the Islamic
tradition that the dome of the mosque opens to allow martyrs to
ascend to heaven.
   It is one of the many military monuments in Baghdad. Another is
made from the wreckage of an Iranian war plane shot down over the
city.
   Madria Nasser Abdul Al-Mishadani, a 40-year-old woman walking
near the Qaddissiya monument, said Iraqi women are not afraid their
loved ones will be killed in another war.
   ``The women are not afraid. Aren't we Iraqis? Why should we be
scared?'' she asked.
   ``Why is the United States so upset over the invasion of
Kuwait?''
   ``The United States had less right to go into Panama than we had
to go into Kuwait,'' she added. ``We have tried to get Kuwait back
for 30 years.''
   A man walking near the monument, 40-year-old Salem Kalaf, said
that during the war with Iran people got used to hardships such as
the reduced consumption that the U.N. trade embargo might bring
again.
   ``We know about war. We saw missiles hit our homes and our
stores. And we lived through that,'' he said.
   The government indicated it will start rationing the sale of
some basic foods in the next few days. But it insisted the measure
was a precaution because of the sanctions and not a response to
shortages.
   Some lines have already formed outside bakeries for bread. But
while some say privately they are worried about shortages, most
Iraqis like Kalaf say publicly they are prepared to endure more
hardships.
   ``I am not afraid. Our country is strong and we can handle
this,'' said Mohammed Hussein, a 47-year-old Baghdad resident, who
said two of his sons were with the army in Kuwait.
   ``I want to tell the American people that their president is not
listening to us. We want peace,'' said Ahmed Abdallah, a
54-year-old Baghdad resident.
   ``It appears that most people do not want a war with Iraq. If
America is a democratic country, then Bush should listen to what
the people are saying.''
</TEXT>
