<LP>
   I enjoyed your May 15 page-one account of Rabbi Eliyahu
Avichail's search for "the 10 Lost Tribes of Israel," but I
did find a discrepancy. You state that the 10 tribes were
dispersed across Asia after the Assyrians smashed the First
Jewish Temple more than 2,700 years ago. It was not the
Assyrians who destroyed the First Jewish Temple in 722 B.C.,
but the Babylonians in 536 B.C.
   The United Kingdom of Israel was ruled first by King Saul,
followed by King David and then by David's son, King Solomon.
David made Jerusalem the capital; the First Temple was built
in Jerusalem by Solomon. Solomon oppressed the people through
heavy spending, taxes and forced labor. After his death, the
people asked his son, King Rehoboam, to lighten the burden of
government on them, but he refused. This denial led the
northern tribes (normally called the 10 tribes) to secede and
form a nation known as Israel under the leadership of King
Jeroboam. The southern tribes stayed true to King Rehoboam,
forming a separate nation known as Judah, with its capital at
Jerusalem.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Israel (the northern confederation) eventually established
its capital at Samaria (north of Jerusalem) under King Omri.
According to the Bible, Israel (NC) displeased God by its
worship of idols, and other sins, and as a result was
conquered by the Assyrians under Shalmaneser in 722 B.C. The
citizens of Israel (NC) were then dispersed as described in
your article.
   Assyria also attempted to conquer Judah in 701 B.C., but
was stopped short at Jerusalem when God intervened.
   Assyria in turn was conquered by Babylon in 626 B.C.
   Babylon under King Nebuchadnezzar defeated Judah in 586
B.C., destroying Jerusalem and the First Temple.
   The people of Judah were deported to Babylon (modern Iraq)
for a period of 70 years. Babylon in turn was defeated by the
Medes and Persians under Cyrus the Great, who allowed the
Jews to return to Palestine to rebuild Jerusalem and the
temple. Persia was later defeated by Greece, which was
defeated by Rome prior to the birth of Jesus Christ.
   Jack W. Hayward Elkhart,
   Kan.
   ---
   As much as I sympathize with Chima Onyeulo (a member of
the Ibo tribe of southern Nigeria) in his quest for a
homeland, it seems to me he has fallen victim to the idea of
"Ibo-Jewry." "Ibo-Jewry" was first proposed by a segment of
the British aristocracy to explain the plight of the Ibos
during the Nigerian-Biafran civil war. Moreover, the
revelations of Innocent the tribesman hardly qualify as an
irrefutable proof of "Ibo-Jewry."
   As a biblical scholar familiar with the Menelik dynasty of
Ethiopia, I can tell you that the only Africans who can
possibly lay any claims to Jewish ancestry are the Ethiopian
Jews. Following the love affair between King Solomon and
Queen Sheba of Sabo, a male offspring named Ebna Hakim, or
Son of the Wise One, was conceived. After his childhood days
in Ethiopia, he was sent to his father in Judea for tutelage.
On his way back to Ethiopia, his father sent some reluctant
scholars and priests to escort him back, thereby ensuring
that the teachings as contained in the "Kebra-Nagest,"
Ethiopia's holiest of books, which he authored, were strictly
adhered to. This is at least one of the versions of the story
of the Jewish migration to Ethiopia.
   The similarities between the Jewish and Ibo socio-cultural
evolution are by no means scientific determinants that result
in Ibo-Jews or Jew-Ibos. These same similarities could
readily exist between Ibos and an ethnic group in Yugoslavia
or in the Russian republic.
   Furthermore, the Ibos are forever grateful to the Jewish
state for the powerful assistance that it rendered during the
Nigerian-Biafran civil war. But that does not by itself
